>>66933947
If you're on an Arch, go on AUR, install `koboldcpp-cuda` (Nvidia, there are other builds for AMD and CPU).

That's the easy part.

The tricky part is the model. There are loads of models on Hugging Face, but you're looking for:
- large context since you want it to rewrite big chunks of text
- fast to rewrite quickly
- accurate and not prone to actually changing the story

The catch 22 is if you're on consumer hardware you probably have one 8GB video card, which means a very small model (7B or 8B class, or a special extra small one) and those are kind dumb. But the next step up is usually something like 70B parameters and those you either have 64 to 128+ GB of video ram across cards, or you accept that it writes about one word per second, which is tolerable but not what you want.

But local is probably the only way you'll get an AI to process a story with those tags >>66933610 without bitching about being Safe and Respectful.

>hosed
Probably for now. The current tech really wants hundreds of GB to be fast.

There is a new kind of LLM model that's gotten some buzz, that could be able to perform like models many times larger that would be a hell of a boon for consumer grade, but it has two problems.
- You can't convert current models so you must start training from scratch
- Training takes a LOT more compute, which means a lot more money to make a model.

Basically it moves much of the work from inference to training. Which in the long run is great but it's a hurdle nobody currently wants to clear when that compute could be spent just pushing the current tech a little farther so they can say "We're the best now, give us money!"

Give it five months and who knows.
